Rift Valley fever, South Africa
-------------------------------
Information received on 8 Feb 2008 from Mr Bothle Michael Modisane,
Assistant Director General, Department of Agriculture, National
Regulatory Services, PRETORIA, South Africa

Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Start date 14 Jan 2008
Date of 1st confirmation of the event 6 Feb 2008
Report date 8 Feb 2008
Date submitted to OIE 8 Feb 2008
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence January 1999
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent Rift Valley fever virus. Genus: _Phlebovirus_. Family:
_Bunyaviridae_
Nature of diagnosis Laboratory (basic), Laboratory (advanced), Necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1 Ngwenya, Ehlanzeni, MPUMALANGA
Date of start of the outbreak 14 Jan 2008
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Farm

Species Buffaloes
Susceptible 371
Cases 5
Deaths 5
Destroyed 0
Slaughtered 0
Affected population buffaloes kept in an enclosure on a game farm.

Summary of outbreaks Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak statistics
Species Buffaloes
Apparent morbidity rate 1.35 percent
Apparent mortality rate 1.35 percent
Apparent case fatality rate 100.00 percent
Proportion susceptible animals lost* 1.35 percent
* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction
and/or slaughter

Epidemiology: Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection. Vectors

Control measures:
Measures applied - Quarantine; No vaccination; No treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied - Screening; Vaccination in response to the outbreak(s)

Diagnostic test results

Species Buffaloes
Test virus isolation
Test date 8 Feb 2008
Result Pending

Laboratory name and type: Agricultural Research Council -
Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (OIE's Reference Laboratory)

Species Buffaloes
Test immunohistochemical test
Test date 6 Feb 2008
Result Positive

Species Buffaloes
Test real-time PCR
Test date 8 Feb 2008
Result Positive

